Partitions — the unit of parallelism.

An R-D-D is split into partitions — chunks of data that can be processed independently. And here is the key fact: each partition is processed by exactly one task, on one executor core.

That one fact sets the degree of parallelism. The number of partitions is the degree of parallelism for that R-D-D. If you have more partitions than cores, some tasks queue up, but every core stays busy. If you have fewer partitions than cores, some cores just sit idle.

There are two defaults worth knowing. After a shuffle, the number of output partitions defaults to the shuffle-partitions setting, which is two hundred unless you change it. And for an R-D-D created with parallelize, the default is the default-parallelism value, which is usually the total number of cores available.

Right-sizing partitions — enough to use every core, but not so many that task-startup overhead takes over — is a theme we return to in the performance-tuning module.
